Illusion Manifold Theory: A Mathematical Framework for Objective Meaning and Semantic Distortion

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

We introduce a rigorous mathematical theory of semantic distortion within the framework of Riemannian geometry and fixed-point theory. Meaning is modeled as points on a Hadamard manifold, interpretation as firmly nonexpansive maps, and semantic illusion as a measurable divergence between true and perceived meaning. We prove the convergence of multi-agent interpretation to a common fixed point under firmly nonexpansive operators via the Fréchet mean, with explicit convergence rates. The framework is extended to stochastic dynamics using Wasserstein contraction, and to self-correcting agents through Riemannian gradient flow on bias parameters. We provide complete, self-contained proofs for all main theorems, establish the theoretical foundations for emergent manifolds in large language models, and derive quantitative convergence rates. This work establishes a purely mathematical foundation for studying meaning, distortion, and alignment, with all results proven in the setting of Hadamard manifolds.

Keywords: Hadamard manifolds, firmly nonexpansive mappings, Fréchet mean, Wasserstein distance, semantic distortion, fixed-point theory, CAT(0) spaces

Mathematics Subject Classification (2020): 53C20, 47H10, 58C05, 49Q22, 91F20

