1. Introduction

Language serves as a bridge between minds, yet this bridge is inherently imperfect. While existing theories focus on representing what meaning is, we instead formalize how meaning becomes distorted in interpretation. We treat meaning as a latent point on a Riemannian manifold, interpretation as a transformation that may contract, expand, or distort, and semantic illusion as a measurable divergence between true and perceived meaning. The central claim, proven rigorously in this work, is that under suitable conditions, multi-agent interpretation converges to a common fixed point—an objective meaning—and that agents can learn to reduce their own distortions through geometric optimization.

This theory draws from several mathematical disciplines:

· Differential geometry provides the language of manifolds, geodesics, and curvature;
· Fixed-point theory on Hadamard manifolds supplies the convergence machinery for nonexpansive operators;
· Optimal transport offers natural metrics for comparing distributions of meanings;
· Information geometry informs the structure of statistical manifolds arising in language models.

A critical review of earlier versions identified several gaps: the existence and uniqueness of fixed points under firmly nonexpansive maps required rigorous treatment, the assumptions on manifold curvature needed consistency, and the proofs demanded complete, self-contained arguments. This version addresses these issues by:

1. Establishing that the Fréchet mean of firmly nonexpansive maps remains firmly nonexpansive on Hadamard manifolds;
2. Proving convergence to a common fixed point with explicit rates using the theory of averaged operators;
3. Providing full proofs in appendices with precise citations to foundational work;
4. Maintaining consistent assumptions throughout: all core results are proven on Hadamard manifolds (complete, simply connected, non-positive curvature).

The paper is organized as follows. Section 2 reviews related literature. Section 3 establishes the geometric foundations. Section 4 presents the dynamical formulation. Section 5 contains the main convergence theorems with complete proofs. Sections 6-8 extend the framework to stochastic dynamics, LLM geometry, and self-correction. Section 9 provides concrete geometric realizations. Section 10 discusses philosophical implications and future directions. Appendices contain detailed proofs.

