2. Literature Review

We situate our work within several mathematical and philosophical traditions:

Philosophical semantics (Montague [20], Grice [11], Wittgenstein [29]) provides the conceptual motivation: meaning is context-dependent and co-constructed, which motivates our use of multiple observers and context spaces.

Distributional semantics (Landauer & Dumais [16], Mikolov et al. [19]) demonstrates that word meanings can be represented in vector spaces; we extend this to curved manifolds.

Information geometry (Amari [2]) provides the Fisher metric for statistical manifolds, which we use to model emergent meaning spaces in language models.

Optimal transport (Villani [28]) gives us Wasserstein distances, natural metrics on probability distributions that we employ to quantify semantic distortion.

Dynamical systems in cognition (van Gelder [27], Hutchins [14]) motivates the fixed-point attractor view of belief formation.

Hyperbolic embeddings (Nickel & Kiela [21], Tifrea et al. [26]) demonstrate that hierarchical concepts naturally embed in hyperbolic space, providing a concrete geometric realization.

Fixed-point theory on Hadamard manifolds (Bačák [5], Afsari et al. [1], Khatibzadeh & Ranjbar [15]) supplies the mathematical machinery for our convergence proofs. The recent literature on firmly nonexpansive mappings on Hadamard manifolds [1, 5, 15, 23] establishes the foundations we build upon.

LLM geometry (Park et al. [22], Saglam et al. [24]) provides empirical evidence for linear subspaces and layerwise structure in transformer models, which we incorporate as constraints on the manifold.

Our novel contribution is a unified geometric-dynamical framework that quantifies semantic distortion and proves convergence of multi-agent interpretation under relaxed contractivity conditions, with complete mathematical rigor.

