6. Stochastic Dynamics

Real interpretation often involves randomness (e.g., sampling in LLMs). We model the update as a Markov chain on $\mathcal{M}$.

6.1 Stochastic Update

Let $\xi_t$ be a random variable taking values in the set of subsets of $\{1,\ldots,N\}$ (or more generally, in the space of maps). The transition kernel $K(p, \cdot)$ is defined by:
M^{(t+1)} = \operatorname{Fr}(\{F_i(M^{(t)})\}_{i \in \xi_t}).

We assume that the random maps are selected i.i.d. from a distribution $\mathbb{P}$ such that $\mathbb{E}[d_g(F_i(p), F_i(q))] \le L d_g(p,q)$ for some $L < 1$.

6.2 Wasserstein Contraction

Theorem 6.1 (Wasserstein Contraction). Suppose the random maps satisfy $\mathbb{E}[d_g(F_i(p), F_i(q))] \le L d_g(p,q)$ with $L < 1$. Then the Markov chain has a unique stationary distribution $\pi$, and for any initial distribution $\mu_0$,
W_2(\mu_t, \pi) \le L^t \, W_2(\mu_0, \pi),


where $\mu_t$ is the distribution at time $t$ and $W_2$ denotes the Wasserstein-2 distance.

Proof. The transition kernel satisfies the Wasserstein contraction property [17, Theorem 2.1]. Specifically,
W_2(\mu_{t+1}, \nu_{t+1}) \le \mathbb{E}[W_2(\mathcal{F}_\xi(\mu_t), \mathcal{F}_\xi(\nu_t))] \le L \, W_2(\mu_t, \nu_t),


where the first inequality follows from the convexity of $W_2$ and the second from the contraction bound. The existence and uniqueness of the stationary distribution follow from the Banach fixed point theorem in the complete metric space of probability measures with the $W_2$ metric [28, Theorem 6.18]. ∎

