9. Concrete Geometric Realizations

9.1 Hyperbolic Geometry (Poincaré Ball Model)

Let $\mathcal{M} = \mathbb{B}^d = \{x \in \mathbb{R}^d : \|x\| < 1\}$ with metric
g_x = \left(\frac{2}{1-\|x\|^2}\right)^2 g_{\text{Euclidean}}.


The distance is
d_{\mathbb{H}}(x,y) = \operatorname{arcosh}\left(1 + 2\frac{\|x-y\|^2}{(1-\|x\|^2)(1-\|y\|^2)}\right).

The Fréchet mean on $\mathbb{H}^d$ is unique and can be computed via the Karcher mean algorithm [12]:
M^{(t+1)} = \exp_{M^{(t)}}\left(\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N \exp_{M^{(t)}}^{-1}(F_i(M^{(t)}))\right).

9.2 Euclidean Subspace

Let $\mathcal{M} = \mathbb{R}^k$ with standard Euclidean metric. Then:

· The Fréchet mean reduces to the arithmetic mean: $\operatorname{Fr}(\{x_i\}) = \frac{1}{N}\sum_i x_i$.
· The distortion energy becomes $W_2(\mu, \delta_M)^2 = \int \|x - M\|^2 d\mu(x)$.
· The update simplifies to $M^{(t+1)} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_i F_i(M^{(t)})$.

9.3 Example: Proximal Operators

A rich class of firmly nonexpansive maps is given by proximal operators [5]. Let $\phi: \mathcal{M} \to \mathbb{R}$ be geodesically convex and lower semicontinuous. The proximal map is defined as:
\operatorname{prox}_{\lambda \phi}(p) = \arg\min_{q \in \mathcal{M}} \left\{\frac{1}{2\lambda} d_g(p,q)^2 + \phi(q)\right\}.

Proposition 9.1 (Firm Nonexpansiveness of Proximal Maps). On a Hadamard manifold, $\operatorname{prox}_{\lambda \phi}$ is firmly nonexpansive.

Proof. The optimality condition for $u = \operatorname{prox}_{\lambda \phi}(p)$ is $-\lambda \nabla \phi(u) \in \exp_u^{-1}(p)$. The monotonicity of the subdifferential $\partial \phi$ yields the firm nonexpansiveness inequality [5, Theorem 5.1.2]. ∎

