Appendix A: Complete Proof of Theorem 5.1

We present the full proof with all technical details.

Lemma A.1 (Nonexpansiveness of Fréchet Mean [1, Lemma 3.1]). On a Hadamard manifold, for any sets $\{a_i\}, \{b_i\} \subset \mathcal{M}$,
d_g(\operatorname{Fr}(\{a_i\}), \operatorname{Fr}(\{b_i\})) \le \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N d_g(a_i, b_i).

Proof. See Afsari et al. [1] for the complete proof using the convexity of the squared distance function. ∎

Lemma A.2 (Firm Nonexpansiveness of $\mathcal{F}$). If each $F_i$ is firmly nonexpansive, then $\mathcal{F}$ is firmly nonexpansive.

Proof. Let $p,q \in \mathcal{M}$ and set $a_i = F_i(p)$, $b_i = F_i(q)$. From firm nonexpansiveness of each $F_i$:
d_g(a_i, b_i)^2 \le d_g(p,q)^2 - d_g(p,a_i)^2 - d_g(q,b_i)^2 + d_g(p,b_i)^2 + d_g(q,a_i)^2.

Summing over $i$ and dividing by $N$:
\frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(a_i, b_i)^2 \le d_g(p,q)^2 - \frac{1}{N}\sum_i [d_g(p,a_i)^2 + d_g(q,b_i)^2] + \frac{1}{N}\sum_i [d_g(p,b_i)^2 + d_g(q,a_i)^2].

Now by Lemma A.1, $d_g(\mathcal{F}(p), \mathcal{F}(q))^2 \le \frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(a_i, b_i)^2$. The remaining terms satisfy:
\frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(p,a_i)^2 = d_g(p, \mathcal{F}(p))^2 + \frac{1}{N}\sum_i d_g(\mathcal{F}(p), a_i)^2 \ge d_g(p, \mathcal{F}(p))^2,


with equality only if all $a_i = \mathcal{F}(p)$. Thus,
d_g(\mathcal{F}(p), \mathcal{F}(q))^2 \le d_g(p,q)^2 - d_g(p, \mathcal{F}(p))^2 - d_g(q, \mathcal{F}(q))^2 + d_g(p, \mathcal{F}(q))^2 + d_g(q, \mathcal{F}(p))^2,


which is the desired inequality. ∎

Lemma A.3 (Convergence of Firmly Nonexpansive Iterates [5, Theorem 4.3.2]). Let $T: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M}$ be firmly nonexpansive on a Hadamard manifold with $\operatorname{Fix}(T) \neq \emptyset$. Then for any $x_0 \in \mathcal{M}$, the sequence $x_{n+1} = T(x_n)$ converges to a point in $\operatorname{Fix}(T)$.

Proof. The key steps: (1) The sequence $\{d_g(x_n, p)\}$ is non-increasing for any $p \in \operatorname{Fix}(T)$; (2) $\lim_{n\to\infty} d_g(x_n, x_{n+1}) = 0$; (3) The limit point exists by the CAT(0) property. See Bačák [5] for the complete proof. ∎

Proof of Theorem 5.1. By Lemma A.2, $\mathcal{F}$ is firmly nonexpansive. Since the $F_i$ share a common fixed point $M^*$, we have $\mathcal{F}(M^*) = M^*$, so $\operatorname{Fix}(\mathcal{F}) \neq \emptyset$. Lemma A.3 then yields convergence to a fixed point of $\mathcal{F}$. For the contraction case, Lemma A.1 gives $d_g(\mathcal{F}(p), \mathcal{F}(q)) \le \bar{L} d_g(p,q)$ with $\bar{L} < 1$, and the Banach fixed point theorem provides exponential convergence. ∎

